            "answer_text": "The expectation value of the energy is conserved - or in less fancy words, it is conserved \u201con average\u201d. Ehrenfest\u2019s theorem gives that: [math]\\frac{d}{dt} \\langle A \\rangle = \\frac{1}{i \\hbar} \\langle [\\hat{A},\\hat{H}] \\rangle + \\langle \\frac{\\partial A}{\\partial t} \\rangle[/math] Where [math]A[/math] is an observable and [math]\\hat{A}[/math] is the associated operator, and [math]\\hat{H}[/math] is the Hamiltonian operator (the energy operator). For energy conservation, [math]A=H:[/math] [math]\\frac{d}{dt} \\langle H \\rangle = \\langle \\frac{\\partial H}{\\partial t} \\rangle[/math] Therefore, if [math]\\hat{H}[/math] is constant in time - then the expectation value of the energy is constant in time. This means you can \u201cborrow\u201d energy for a small amount of time - but you can't \u201ckeep\u201d it. The variance in this \u201caverage\u201d can be gleaned from the energy-time version of the uncertainty principle: [math] \u0394t \u0394E \\geq \\frac{\\hbar}{2}[/math] ",
